<header>
<a href="/blog/2013/07/11/eclipse-quick-search"><h2 class="member-post--title">Eclipse Quick Search</h2></a>
<div class="meta-data--container">
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon engineering"></div>
<a class="category" href="/blog/category/engineering">Engineering</a>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon calendar"></div>
<time class="date" pubdate="" datetime="2013-07-11 19:53:00.0">July 11, 2013</time>
</div>
</div>
</header>
<section class="member-post--summary"><p>Are you an Eclipse user? Do you want a fast and easy way to search for text snippets and patterns in your workspace? Then read on!</p>
<p>A new “Quick Search” is included in Spring ToolSuite (STS) 3.3.0 and Groovy Gails Tool Suite (GGTS) 3.3.0 which have just been released. Even if you are not a Spring or Grails developer, you might be interested in this Feature because it can also be installed separately into a vanilla Eclipse.<br></p>
<h2>Introducing the Quick Search Dialog</h2>
<br>
<p></p>
<p>You open the dialog by pressing <strong>CTRL+SHIFT+L</strong> (or <strong>CMD+SHIFT+L</strong> on Mac):</p>
</section>
<a class="blog-preview--readmore" href="/blog/2013/07/11/eclipse-quick-search">
Read more...
</a>
</article>
